Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: can someone explain to me in simple words what is the difference between this and for example nicehash miner apart from payout in their coin instead of btc?

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: It's not the miner that makes us unique, it's the platform - you have stats of your rigs, profitability of coins are being constantly recalculated and you're mining the most profitable coin at any given time. Stake Mining impacts your mining revenue - and once we're on exchanges and one's able to bid on renting speed you won't be limited to bid restrained by the bitcoin's value. that means potentially more revenue for the bidder and more revenue for the miner, whereas nicehash will only get you 5-10%+ the average revenue.  TLDR - this is not just just a pool, this is a complete "ecosystem" built around a coin dedicated to users that miner cryptocurrency.

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: What do you mean won't accept your password? Just tested and uppercase works. Also I don't know what you're trying to do since the client doesn't even requires a password but the secret code and email. About the speed - it's about roughly 3% lower than Claymore because I am using ethminer. Am much aware of the problem and will definitely be fixed with the beta. I am very much aware that there might be some bugs, it's an Alpha. I wouldn't launch an ICO if I had a finished product. This is just a small sample of what the actual platform and miner is supposed to do and it's obviously buggy but it should so the job and we're constantly fixing bugs. If you still have troubles please message me. I'm glad to help.

Author: xaeder
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Okay, so:  - Forgot Password feature doesn't work - when you enter your email, it just resets the page and no email arrives to reset it - Some accounts require activation, others didn't - Even though it reads for example ETC as most profitable, it still goes for Verge, and when I manually put back ETC, the Coin gain was higher - All GPUs are on maximum load, yet hashrate is around 40-50% of what claymore or ethminer do regularly - Miner is unstable, causes system crashes, maybe it's only a multi GPU problem, tested with 6x GPU rig - I tried letting it hash for an hour, counting on sharecount to come to a more precise average, but it was still below 50% of the regular hashrate - You should make an auto refresh feature for the dashboard, but overall it's fine. Reports with only a slight delay compared to the client - Some graphic improvements for the client are necessary, the settings menu where you choose coins is a bit glitched  I'll continue testing it for a few days, and hoping to see improvement!

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: First of all thanks for taking the time to submit the bugs. Appreciate it.  - we managed to fix the password reset feature - about the account requiring activation, we're still working on trying to see what's causing the problem - the update rate of the miner was set to 30 minutes, that's why the profitability was recalculated more often but the miner didn't switch between the coins (we used 30 mins because it might cause increase in resources and might cause crashes) - we've lowered the time period and now it should be updated every 2 to 5 minutes so it should fix the problem  - we've implemented an auto refresh feature on the dashboard, it's now refreshing every 1 min - the slight delay is of less than 1 minute because the miner is sending the updates every 1 minute, doing it any faster will increase the resource usage on the miner and it's just not worth it for anyone - we've fixed the settings glitch in the next update, it's already on site you can redownload it  - now about the averages and the hast rate: the averages calculated on site are just taking in account the last submitted speed, that's why the variations, but in reality both the revenue and speed are more stable. - also part of the variations come from ethminer, but again it shouldn't be reflected on the revenue rate overall - as for the 40-50% hashrate I think it's something on your end, it should definitely get +95% of the normal speed  - as for the crashes, mind giving some more details on when is it happening?

Author: xaeder
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Okay, went through further testing  - Password reset is working as intended, managed to reset on what i wanted to be my main account, great! - The glitch in the client for coins settings has been fixed, but now it doesn't give me any graphical confirmation that i selected any of the coins. I suggest to just add highlight to the chosen coin when clicked - Refresh is great, unnoticeable, works properly - The hashrate shown in the dashboard is always in MH, even though some coins are in KHs - I'm also very skeptic about the accuracy, it gives around 5-7MH on scrypt (emc2), which is far more than I usually get, I suggest putting scrypt and x11 coins in a seperate place for people with asics - For some reason changing the coin works only for a few minutes then it returns it to whatever it was previously, so i couldnt test ethhash extensively, just emc2 - The hashrate on ethhash is like 30% of what i should have, that's something definitely with the client compatibility, have you tested it on various CUDA versions, drivers, etc? It's not my rig, i get full hashrate via any console miner. For the record, I'm using CUDA 9, unfortunately don't have a place to test it on earlier versions. But it shouldnt really make that much of a difference since I used both ethminer and claymore with full hashrate, I really have no clue what's the bottleneck. - The system crashes occur randomly after 30 mins or so, tested with both base clocks, underclock, overclock, with different drivers, always the same outcome. The only thing i notice is while it's running, a window in the background (in my case afterburner) keeps minimizing and restoring every 30 secs or so. Shouldn't really happen.  Waiting for further update, thanks dev!

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Hey, thanks for resubmitting again - regarding the glitch with the selected coins, I used white for the selected coin and I guess your monitor brightness is custom and you might not see it. I've changed it now to grey, so it should be visible on any monitor - I fixed the stupid bug in the dashboard regarding the speed - changing the coin should work now and custom mining / non auto also should  The update is on site.  Now, regarding the speed. First just go into the /miners file and launch the start.bat Let me know if the speed is stable for ETH. If it is, then it means our miner is using too many resources and it's killing speed. If it's not and the speed is also low, then I guess it's ethminer's version. What gpu's are you using?  Now about crashes. Once every 90 seconds the miner tries to update the temperature and the fans, this might cause slight issues with some gpu versions. Make sure you're running the miner as admin firstly. Also, check to see if the CPU usage is really high.

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Hey, thanks for the positive feedback. As far as I understand you're asking about the revenue system and how will it be rewarding the miners, right? Here's the complete formula of the revenue per minute:  (base_value + coin_profitability_bonus + active_users_bonus + stake_miners_bonus) * rig_speed * 60 seconds  base_value = variable that's depending on the CryptoSoftCoin's market value coin_profitability_bonus = the mined coin's profitability (there's a chart on the /dashboard of the platform)                                     - now the profitability is proportional to the mined coin's value                                     - and inverse proportional to the mining difficulty                                     - so, to conclude we don't care about the coin's price, but about the coin's profitability  active_users_bonus = variable that's depending on the number of active miners on the platform stake_miners_bonus = more or less bonus depending if the stake miners predict right or wrong

Author: TheKryptonian
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Some questions:  Am I correct in noting that miners are being paid in CryptoSoft Coins for mining?  If so, what is happening with the coins actually being mined (like ETH right now)?  Is the ETH being mined sold for USD?  Who is keeping that USD? You?  So If miners are being paid in CryptoSoft Coin constantly, that means they will be constantly dumping the CryptoSoft Coin on an exchange.  What is going to drive pressure on the buy side of the CryptoSoft Coin?  It seems the value of the coin will only increase if stake miners are guessing correctly what currencies will appreciate in value.  But if I'm an investor, and I have a good guess as to what currency will increase, why wouldn't I just invest in that currency directly?  Why would I choose instead to buy CryptoSoft Coin and vote for that coin?

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Great questions, there will be a limited amount of CryptoCoins - that means we will have to use the ETH (for example) to rebuy some of our coins from the market. There will mainly be 3 people buying the coin - the ones that are looking to hold and hope to make money from the coin raising, the stake miners and us. You, as an investor would rather chose to stake mine because you will be making a higher ROI by staking than buying the actual coin. Similar to buying and selling stocks in a way.  I don't think the value of the coin is directly affected by the fact that stake miners guess right or wrong. The ones that are directly affected are miners.

Author: TheKryptonian
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Thank you for responding.  I don't think your whitepaper actually says you will use the underlying mined coins to repurchase CryptoCoins.  And in fact, unless you commit to using 100% of the mined earnings to buy CryptoCoins, it sounds like you will be keeping a bonus on top of the mining fee, so I think the % you are committing to allocate to purchasing should be made clear so that people know how much you are keeping.   Sorry if the whitepaper does explain this and I just missed it.

Author: AndreiBucaciuc
Title: ðŸ“ŒLIVE - Round 3 [CryptoSoft] - The first complete CryptoMining ecosystem!
Body: Yeah, you're right I think I ought to mention the rebuying part and I will make sure to add it in the next 24 hours. As for the % I am not sure I'm able to give one because it will be really up to the miners, coin market's price and a whole lot of other variables to consider. But the goal is always to have enough coins available to pay the miners for their effort and the stake miners for their winnings. But indeed, a given percentage makes things more transparent and I will think of a solution and update the Whitepaper. Thanks.
